## Create and publish a release

```bash
npm run plugin:pack
```

For a durable GitHub Release, merge a release-content change to `main`. The
generated workflow preserves an explicit unreleased version from the PR or
automatically increments the latest released patch version, synchronizes
`package.json` and `opsrabbit.plugin.json`, commits that version, tags the exact
commit, and publishes the release. Set an explicit higher version in the PR for
a minor or major release.

The workflow ignores README-, AGENTS-, test-, coverage-, workflow-, and
generated-release-only changes. Automatic patch commits require GitHub Actions
write access to `main`; if branch protection blocks the bot, set the next
version explicitly in the PR so no bot commit is required. Manual immutable
tags remain supported for recovery. For version `1.2.3`:

```bash
git tag v1.2.3
git push origin v1.2.3
```

The generated `Plugin Release` workflow reruns the quality gates and publishes
the deterministic ZIP, SHA-256 checksum, SPDX 2.3 SBOM, and release metadata.
It also creates a GitHub artifact-provenance attestation when the repository
plan supports that feature; checksum/SBOM publication remains available when
attestation does not. A tag is rejected unless it exactly matches the manifest
and package version. To inspect
the same assets locally before tagging, run:

```bash
npm run plugin:release -- --tag v1.2.3
```

Upload the ZIP under `release/` (manual pack) or `release-assets/` (release set)
in the OpsRabbit Plugins administration UI.
Download the explicitly named ZIP asset, not GitHub's automatic **Source code
(zip)** archive, which is not a deployable plugin bundle.
Uploading does not activate a plugin: a deployment administrator must review its
identity, provenance, capabilities, and compatibility before activation.

`opsrabbit.plugin.json` is authoritative. `src/index.ts` registers behavior, and
`plugin:check` rejects undeclared or mismatched registrations.
It loads the compiled entry to perform that comparison, so run it only on
source you trust, just like this repository's build and test scripts.

Do not commit credentials. Plugins receive only capability-scoped host services;
they must not connect directly to the OpsRabbit database or internal endpoints.
